---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "5-6 Year Milestones: Kindergarten Development Checklist",
  "description": "Complete developmental milestones checklist for 5-6 year olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social-emotional milestones for kindergarten age.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "AgeExpectations"
  }
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What milestones should a 5-year-old achieve?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "At 5, most children can hop on one foot, write some letters, count to 20, tell simple stories, and play cooperatively with rules. They should be mostly understandable when speaking."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should a 6-year-old be able to do?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "At 6, most children can skip, print letters and numbers, read simple words, tell time to the hour, and follow multi-step directions. They have established friendships and can manage emotions with support."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When do children learn to read?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most children learn to read between ages 5-7. Some read earlier, some later — both can be normal. Kindergarten and first grade are when formal reading instruction typically begins."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="5-6 Year Milestones: Kindergarten Development Checklist" description="Complete developmental milestones checklist for 5-6 year olds. Physical, cognitive, language, and social milestones for kindergarten age." schema={schema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>5-6 Year Milestones: Development Checklist</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 5-6 years · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/5-6-years/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/5-6-years/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/5-6-years/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/5-6-years/behavior/">Behavior</a>
      <a href="/ages/5-6-years/school/">School</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>The years between 5 and 6 bring remarkable changes as children transition from preschoolers to students. This guide covers the developmental milestones to expect, based on CDC and AAP guidelines.</p>

      <h2>5 Year Milestones</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Stands on one foot for 10 seconds or longer</li>
        <li>Hops; may be able to skip</li>
        <li>Can do a somersault</li>
        <li>Uses a fork and spoon and sometimes a table knife</li>
        <li>Can use the toilet on their own</li>
        <li>Swings and climbs</li>
        <li>Copies triangle and other geometric patterns</li>
        <li>Draws a person with body and limbs</li>
        <li>Prints some letters or numbers</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Speaks very clearly</li>
        <li>Tells a simple story using full sentences</li>
        <li>Uses future tense ("Grandma will be here")</li>
        <li>Says name and address</li>
        <li>Understands rhyming</li>
        <li>Knows about things used every day (money, food, appliances)</li>
        <li>Vocabulary of 2,000+ words</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Counts 10 or more things</li>
        <li>Can draw a person with at least 6 body parts</li>
        <li>Can print some letters or numbers</li>
        <li>Copies a triangle and other geometric shapes</li>
        <li>Knows about things used every day (money, food, appliances)</li>
        <li>Understands the concept of time (morning, afternoon, tomorrow)</li>
        <li>Can follow 2-3 step instructions</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Wants to please friends</li>
        <li>Wants to be like friends</li>
        <li>More likely to agree with rules</li>
        <li>Likes to sing, dance, and act</li>
        <li>Is aware of gender</li>
        <li>Can tell what's real and what's make-believe</li>
        <li>Shows more independence</li>
        <li>Is sometimes demanding and sometimes very cooperative</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>6 Year Milestones</h2>
      
      <h3>Physical/Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Can skip, gallop, and jump rope</li>
        <li>Can ride a bike (some without training wheels)</li>
        <li>Prints letters and numbers clearly</li>
        <li>Copies complex shapes</li>
        <li>Ties shoelaces (with practice)</li>
        <li>Uses utensils proficiently</li>
        <li>Dresses self completely</li>
        <li>Bathes self (with supervision)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Language/Communication</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Speaks in complex sentences</li>
        <li>Can tell and retell stories in sequence</li>
        <li>Understands jokes and riddles</li>
        <li>Asks questions to gain information</li>
        <li>Uses most speech sounds correctly</li>
        <li>May stutter when excited or upset (usually temporary)</li>
        <li>Enjoys wordplay and rhymes</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cognitive</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Counts to 100 by ones and tens</li>
        <li>Recognizes and writes numbers to 20</li>
        <li>Knows basic addition and subtraction</li>
        <li>Understands concepts of time (yesterday, today, tomorrow)</li>
        <li>Can tell time to the hour</li>
        <li>Knows days of the week</li>
        <li>Understands cause and effect</li>
        <li>Can group objects by multiple characteristics</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Social/Emotional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Has established friendships</li>
        <li>Understands rules and fair play</li>
        <li>Shows empathy for others</li>
        <li>Can manage emotions with support</li>
        <li>Seeks approval from adults</li>
        <li>May be critical of self and others</li>
        <li>Enjoys group activities and games</li>
        <li>Can separate from parents for school</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Reading Readiness</h2>
      <p>Before formal reading instruction, children typically show:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Interest in books and stories</li>
        <li>Recognizes own name in print</li>
        <li>Knows some letters and their sounds</li>
        <li>Understands that print carries meaning</li>
        <li>Can retell a simple story</li>
        <li>Recognizes some common words (stop, exit, their name)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Some children read before kindergarten; others learn in first grade. Both are within the normal range.</p>

      <h2>Math Concepts</h2>
      <p>Early math skills include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Counts objects accurately</li>
        <li>Recognizes written numbers</li>
        <li>Understands one-to-one correspondence</li>
        <li>Sorts objects by attributes</li>
        <li>Recognizes simple patterns</li>
        <li>Understands "more" and "less"</li>
        <li>Knows basic shapes</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Fine Motor Development</h2>
      <p>Hand skills important for school:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Holds pencil with tripod grip</li>
        <li>Draws recognizable pictures</li>
        <li>Writes some letters and numbers</li>
        <li>Uses scissors to cut along lines</li>
        <li>Colors within lines</li>
        <li>Manages buttons, zippers, snaps</li>
        <li>Pours without spilling</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Red Flags: When to Be Concerned</h2>
      <p>Talk to your pediatrician if your child:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Can't jump in place or hop on one foot</li>
        <li>Can't draw a circle, square, or simple person</li>
        <li>Can't brush teeth, wash and dry hands, or get undressed</li>
        <li>Can't use the toilet independently</li>
        <li>Can't retell a favorite story</li>
        <li>Speech is not understandable to strangers</li>
        <li>Can't follow two-part instructions</li>
        <li>Doesn't play with other children</li>
        <li>Extreme behavior (fearful, aggressive, shy, withdrawn)</li>
        <li>Can't correctly name colors</li>
        <li>Can't understand the difference between real and make-believe</li>
        <li>Doesn't talk about daily activities or experiences</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Supporting Development</h2>
      <p>Activities that help 5-6 year olds thrive:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Reading together:</strong> Daily reading builds literacy skills</li>
        <li><strong>Games:</strong> Board games teach turn-taking and rules</li>
        <li><strong>Physical play:</strong> Running, climbing, bike riding</li>
        <li><strong>Arts and crafts:</strong> Drawing, cutting, building</li>
        <li><strong>Chores:</strong> Age-appropriate tasks build responsibility</li>
        <li><strong>Conversation:</strong> Talk about their day, answer questions</li>
        <li><strong>Playdates:</strong> Social skills develop through interaction</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Is This Normal? — Common Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My child can't read yet at 6. Should I be worried?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">No — most children learn to read between ages 5-7. If your child is progressing in other areas and shows interest in books, they're likely on track. First grade is when many children really take off with reading.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My kindergartener still reverses letters. Is this dyslexia?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Letter reversals are very common through age 7 and are usually not a sign of dyslexia. Children are still learning the visual forms of letters. If reversals persist beyond second grade or come with other concerns, discuss with your pediatrician.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Should my 5-year-old know all their letters?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Recognition of some letters (especially those in their name) is helpful, but knowing all letters is not required for kindergarten success. Kindergarten is designed to teach letter recognition and sounds.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My child is left-handed. Should I try to change this?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">No — handedness is determined by the brain and should not be changed. Left-handed children may need left-handed scissors and may write with a different pencil grip, but they develop normally.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
